I beleve the economy in the metroplex is strong enough to recover , your silly to think it will completly ruin the job market. Even when the Tech market went uder if you had skills you found work if you looked for it.We are not a city built on AA's exsistence, can you say Telcom corridor, GM , Ford ? <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I never said it would completely ruin the job market.  I said it would send unemployment skyrocketing.  There's a distinct difference.  Will it ruin the economy around DFW?  No, but several businesses and individuals outside the travel and cargo industry will bear a burden if AA goes under.  To think otherwise is to display ignorance about how a local economy works.  Especially when it comes to unemployment.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
How are we being held hostage?? The millions and millions of dollars in tax cuts we have to give them so we can keep here for one . And you stated it yourself ,The fact that if they do go under we are gonna have a high unemployment rate , they hold these things over us and demand less commitment to the area's taxation and development.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In one paragraph you say that if AA went under, it wouldn't have much of an effect.  Yet here you say they are using it as a bargaining chip to leverage tax breaks.  Which is it?  It's niether, really.  American has never threatened to move it's headquarters or even it's DFW hub since originally establishing this area as their base of operations.  Even when the state legislature repealed the Wright Ammendment that restricted flights into and out of Love field, American used it's voice to lobby against it (though, I disagreed with that voice); however, they never threatened to relocate when that would have been the course taken by many companies.  As for these tax incentives, I'm not aware of any that other large companies in this area don't also receive.  Please provide some sort of evidence to contradict me and I'll happily admit error.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I'd be foolish to say it there would be no effect but we would get over it . We are a diverse economy and i feel we could rebound . Also i belive smaller companies would fill the gaps it's going under would create.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That may only be partially true.  No other carrier has the infrastructure to fill the gap American would leave in Texas.  Every other carrier that might fill that void either lacks the capacity to do so (such as Southwest) or isn't financially able to do so (such as Delta and United).  Eventually the smaller carriers may be able to, but the amount of time that will take is going to make travel and cargo in this area extremely rough for a while.<br>
<br>
