<br>
Sorry. I've been through enough corporate reorganizations, downsizing and outright collapses that I'll happily given them my empathy but not a dime out of my wallet. Jobs should exist where is there demand for them to exist, not where it is demanded they exist. Just because you're a really swell flight attendent does not mean that the world needs you to be one. <br>
<br>
About half (maybe more than half) of American's fleet of aircraft are repainted TWA planes. There is absolutely no reason whatsoever that those planes couldn't be repainted again. The routes that American covers that are currently profitable would be snatched up by other airlines, along some of the equipment and personnel currently employed by American to service those routes. The routes that were not profitable would also be snatched up, because nonprofitable routes only exist due to the pricing structures airlines bend time and space to produce.<br>
<br>
Lots of people would still be unemployed, but only because there really wasn't any demand for what they did in the first place. Them's the breaks, time to learn some new skills!<br>
<br>
Anyhow.<br>
<br>
I can't tell you how sick and tired I am of hearing variants on this statement:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The world we live in is completely differently than those who penned our constitution. It would be interesting to see how close to the original it’d be if they re-wrote it today.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You know how they'd write it? They would strive to ensure the government is always entirely beholden to the people which it serves and not vice versa, just like they wrote it the first fucking time. You put a bunch of guys who share not much more than a stark distrust for formal systems of state power in a room and tell them to write up a constitution for a new country and you're gonna get about the same document every time.<br>
<br>
If someone were to actually draw up a constitution today the &quot;completely different world we live in&quot; would only result in a document about 750,000 pages long and adminstered by a squad a lawyers large enough to fill three entire Holidy Inn Express locations. But they'd probably be a tad more specific about in just what context they provide the right of the citizenry right to bear arms.<br>
